        <body>       
                 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Brighton District. Boston. Mass<lb/>
                Janry 31<hi rend="sup">st</hi>. 1888.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev Dr S. Morais&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Esteemed Friend&#44;<lb/> As it is said that &#34;the brave are always<lb/> tender&#44;&#34; so it is true that the truly great<lb/> are always humble.  Finding in your teachings<lb/> these invariably sterling qualities&#44; I could not<lb/> refrain from expressing my reverence.  Moral<lb/> courage is so rare a possession in these<lb/> days of all manner of compromise&#44; great<lb/> though the advance is in some direction.<lb/>  Thanking you for the acceptance of my<lb/> humble tribute&#44; I write this only for the<lb/> purpose of assuring you that what I have<lb/> said contains neither flattery nor exaggeration&#44;<lb/> but comes from my heart.  If all manner<lb/> of language were not so imperfect&#44; I could<lb/> say much more in honest praise and profound<lb/> reverence&#44; &#40;no less&#41; of your character and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>your efforts in behalf of<lb/> Judaism.  You are Orthodox&#44; and I call<lb/> myself a Reformer&#44; but still we meet<lb/> on the broad&#44; common&#44; and yet holy ground<lb/> of our beautiful faith.  With you&#44; in a<lb/> so far lowlier sphere of effort&#44; I advocate<lb/> the restoration in all its ancient honor<lb/> of the Jewish Sabbath&#59; to be retained at<lb/> the cost of&#44; and because of the sacrifices<lb/> of ease and gain that it entails.<lb/></p>
            <p>One more object I have in writing this to<lb/> you&#44; Rev Sir&#59; that you may from<lb/> time to time remember me in your pray&#45;<lb/>ers.  I am alone&#44; and my physical strength<lb/> is departing with the years that now num&#45;<lb/>ber Sixty three.  I have lived in affluence&#44;<lb/> and now I am poor&#59; and I have not<lb/> one tie of kindred in this world.  That I<lb/> may have strength to bear on&#44; and to prove<lb/> worthy of the ancestral name&#44; the prayers<lb/> of the just and merciful can help me.  For<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>such as you whose uplifting of<lb/> the heart and soul has become the habitude<lb/> of life&#44; the might of supplication avails with<lb/> Him who is our God&#44; and the Father of<lb/> all.  Thanking you for your appreciation<lb/> of my imperfect lines&#44; I am most gratefully<lb/> as the recipient of much spiritual good of<lb/> your hands&#44; your friend&#44;<lb/> Cora Wilburn.<lb/></p>
            </body>
